@startuml Contract Rejected — Wrong Purpose
title **Contract Policy Enforcement: Wrong Purpose**\nA corporate actor tries to use research data for ESG reporting

skinparam backgroundColor #FEFEFE
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam sequenceParticipantBorderColor #424242
skinparam sequenceLifeLineBorderColor #9E9E9E
skinparam noteBackgroundColor #FFF9C4
skinparam noteBorderColor #F9A825
skinparam sequenceGroupBackgroundColor #FFEBEE
skinparam sequenceGroupBorderColor #C62828

actor "ESG Analyst\n(Corporate partner)" as Analyst #FFF3E0
participant "Corporate\nEDC Connector" as CORP_EDC #E3F2FD
participant "Caney Fork\nEDC Connector" as CF_EDC #E8F5E9

== Catalog Discovery (succeeds — asset uses members-only access) ==

Analyst -> CORP_EDC : Browse Caney Fork catalog
CORP_EDC -> CF_EDC : DSP Catalog Query

CF_EDC -> CF_EDC : Evaluate **members-only** access policy
note right of CF_EDC
  glcdi_membership == "active" ? **YES**
  (Corporate partner is an active member)
  => Asset is **visible**
end note

CF_EDC --> CORP_EDC : Catalog with grazing rotation offer\n(contract: **benchmarking-terms**)
CORP_EDC --> Analyst : Shows offer

note over Analyst
  The analyst sees the grazing rotation
  data and wants to use it for their
  company's Scope 3 emissions report.
  The contract terms say: benchmarking
  or internal analysis only.
end note

== Contract Negotiation (fails — wrong purpose) ==

Analyst -> CORP_EDC : Accepts terms\npurpose = "Scope3Reporting"
CORP_EDC -> CF_EDC : Contract negotiation\n(purpose = "Scope3Reporting")

group Contract Policy Evaluation [REJECTED] #FFEBEE
  CF_EDC -> CF_EDC : Evaluate **benchmarking-terms**
  note right of CF_EDC #FFCDD2
    purpose in ["RegionalBenchmarking",
    "InternalAnalysis"] ?

    "Scope3Reporting" is **NOT** in the
    permitted purpose list.

    => **NEGOTIATION REJECTED**
  end note
end

CF_EDC --> CORP_EDC : Contract negotiation TERMINATED\n(policy not satisfied)
CORP_EDC --> Analyst : Negotiation failed:\npurpose not permitted

note over Analyst
  **What happened:**
  The corporate analyst could **see** the offer
  (members-only access policy passed) but
  could not **negotiate a contract** because
  the intended purpose (Scope 3 reporting)
  doesn't match the allowed purposes.

  **What the analyst should do:**
  1. Look for assets with a
     **supply-chain-terms** contract
     that explicitly permits Scope3Reporting
  2. Contact the data provider to request
     a new contract definition with
     appropriate terms (may require
     payment + anonymisation)
  3. Work with the GLCDI governance team
     to establish a corporate data access
     agreement
end note

@enduml
